    "body": "Hi there, I am trying to initialise starship in a ZSH terminal on Windows and I am getting the same issue. The full error looks like:\r\n\r\n```sh\r\n/proc/self/fd/14:92: no such file or directory: Files/starship/bin/starship.exe prompt --terminal-width=\"$COLUMNS\" --keymap=\"${KEYMAP:-}\" --status=\"$STARSHIP_CMD_STATUS\" --pipestatus=\"${STARSHIP_PIPE_STATUS[*]}\" --cmd-duration=\"${STARSHIP_DURATION:-}\" --jobs=\"$STARSHIP_JOBS_COUNT\")\r\n/proc/self/fd/14:93: no such file or directory: Files/starship/bin/starship.exe prompt --right --terminal-width=\"$COLUMNS\" --keymap=\"${KEYMAP:-}\" --status=\"$STARSHIP_CMD_STATUS\" --pipestatus=\"${STARSHIP_PIPE_STATUS[*]}\" --cmd-duration=\"${STARSHIP_DURATION:-}\" --jobs=\"$STARSHIP_JOBS_COUNT\")\r\n```\r\n\r\n I do believe that my shell has `cygpath` available.\r\n\r\nAfter doing a bit of digging, I think that maybe the issue is that `PROMPT` and `RPROMPT` variables in the [starship.zsh](https://github.com/starship/starship/blob/099539fd1aa2937e9507a318becffcbc685b83b8/src/init/starship.zsh#L92) init file are wrapped by single quotes instead of double quotes so when the windows path gets loaded as '/c/Program Files/...', the single quotes cause confusion.\r\n\r\nI copied the output of `'/c/Program Files/starship/bin/starship.exe' init zsh --print-full-init` into a temporary zsh file and those two lines look like:\r\n![image](https://github.com/starship/starship/assets/20258546/add47b3e-fe3a-4a6f-b1ea-eaac04b7f130)\r\n\r\nIf I change to wrapping double quotes instead, then I can source the file.\r\n![image](https://github.com/starship/starship/assets/20258546/cc08a467-bc34-406e-b633-5c5222aab2dd)\r\n\r\n~If you agree that this is the root issue, I have made a [PR](https://github.com/starship/starship/pull/5510) to change the quote type.~\r\n\r\nUPDATE:\r\nChanging the quotes solves the sourcing error, but then the prompts don't update at all so a different solution is needed. ",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
